Back in 2016, when people didn’t know a lot about Mandalas, a lot of them asked me if I used any special pen for them. Surprise surprise! I didn’t. I used a very basic black gel pen. 

Later, I did use #MicronPens and #sakuragellyrollpens too. They were fantastic to work with. And you can see, if you scroll down, they took my Mandala to a whole new level. 

During this lockdown, all I had was my simple black pen (since all of my stationery’s at my hostel, in Delhi). For a long time, I couldn’t order them on Amazon either. 

So, here’s another Mandala that I’d made during the Lockdown using a simple #blackpen. Again, you can notice how my creativity was not up to the mark and I forced myself to complete this one! ?

Thank you July for reinstating my faith in life ! And hello August ! 

We may all be sailing in the same boat but we are all facing different storms. There is a bit of a dark shadow looming still in the horizon but am bringing my own sunshine in this monsoon ! I am grateful for July , for all the wonderful workshops , the learning and sharing and for some wonderful collaborations especially with three lovely ladies , @knowledge_santa @malinigs and the inspiring @a_dash_of_panache . I have learnt so much this entire month that I haven’t in the last seven months . I am so humbled and grateful . 

#Throwback to the quaint and ancient Transfiguration Monastery near Veliko Ta?rnovo, the erstwhile capital of the Second Bulgarian Empire in Bulgaria . I have been writing all my Bulgaria stories during the lockdown and am now on the last story , writing about my trip to Veliko Ta?rnovo . There are totally about seven stories and I started writing them in April and am glad that I have managed to write , even if it’s a wee bit everyday. 

When the lockdown began , I told my therapist that I don’t see hope or joy anywhere , a purpose or a goal . I had plunged into gloom and wanted to just retreat into my dark corner . She said to take one day at a time and to write an intention everyday . And I still keep that ritual going . I start the day with my gratitude statement and then with my affirmations and intentions . I meditate for ten minutes before starting my day. And that in a way has kept me going . Let’s all hope that August brings us more cheer and takes us to safer shores away from all the many storms .

I cook it how I like it.

My Backyard Stories
----------------------------
The uninvited guest 
••••••••••••••••••
Rain marks the begining of a new life, literally and figuratively! 
A creeper plant, that has no bounds on how it will grow to where, had decided to creep into our small balcony, from our neighbors garden. A little mess as it seemed in the beginning when we were all locked down, inside our homes, frustrated that we couldn't step out, was an uninvited guest in disguise. Sooner, the small creeper has become a part of our everyday life. Little it seemed, so negligent it's existence was in our daily lives, sooner became our little pet. Of course we didn't nurture it nor gave our undeviating attention. But we did use to observe its growth and also the bright green leaves and it's curly tentacle. A month back, with the beginning of rain after a break of few months, we started seeing the blossoming of flowers on it. Which soon will be an exotic fruit, Passion fruit. 
Very recently, our landlord has cut down the creeper that was growing wildly over our balcony, in fear of any threat from reptiles or also the inconveniences it can cause to the luxury of our human lives. Now the creeper is a controlled plant in our neighbors courtyard. But, it has become one of ours. We see it everyday, budding and blossoming! 
.

Tonga’s capital city during lockdown.⁣
⁣
Tonga went into lockdown a few days after I arrived. It lasted 3 weeks and was very strict. I had to go through about 7 police checkpoints to go shopping, only 30 minutes away. ⁣
⁣
This is how Nukualofa, the capital city of Tonga looked during that time. There’s 100,000 people in Tonga - 70,000 of which live on this island. And they all stayed home. ⁣
⁣
This is how I first met Tonga. Closed shops, bars, restaurants. No one really around, no one wanting to get close to you. There were no cars in the street and no life. This is how I thought Tonga was like - that’s all I knew of the country. ⁣
⁣
It’s now August, and I’ve almost been here for 4.5 months. Nukualofa looks a lot different now. And the people are different, too. Open, friendly, smiling. The restaurants, the bars and cafes, they’re all open - and a lot of them full. There’s cars everywhere and some crazy drivers to go with them too. ⁣
⁣
And I’m so happy to see a new Tonga and a new energy here. I still don’t know how long it will be before I can leave - but I’ll keep trying to make the most of it until then. ⁣
⁣
And 8 months after the outbreak of Coronavirus began, Tonga still remains one of the few countries in the world without Coronavirus. ⁣
⁣
And I hope for Tonga that they can stay this way. ? ?? ⁣

Licious are selling some of the best and tasty spreads for us and my favorite is shawarma spread. Its so yummy with tiny pieces of chicken in it.
